00:00:21.610 --> 00:00:25.560
PROFESSOR: So we have
organized three lectures.

00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:29.520
And the basic idea
of the lectures

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:35.120
are to cover some of
the major current issues

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:39.940
in nuclear arms control
and nonproliferation.

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:47.020
So we have the first lecture
today on India and Pakistan,

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:53.170
which is one of the world's
possible flash points,

00:00:53.170 --> 00:01:00.380
meaning that there's a path to
a possible nuclear war, which

00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:05.190
I won't go into Vipin Narang
will certainly spell out

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:06.440
the case.

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:12.170
But in my view in trying to
decide what to talk about,

00:01:12.170 --> 00:01:15.630
this was a golden opportunity
because Vipin is here,

00:01:15.630 --> 00:01:19.700
and he's an expert
on these issues.

00:01:19.700 --> 00:01:24.440
And I consider this, as I
say, one of the possible flash

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:29.860
points in the world, one of
the possible conceivable paths.

00:01:29.860 --> 00:01:34.610
No path is super likely, if
you want to put it that way.

00:01:34.610 --> 00:01:37.740
But the effects of
a nuclear exchange

00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:43.080
are catastrophic both for the
people who get hit, obviously,

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:46.350
because a nuclear weapon--
I don't have to tell you--

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:48.690
is incredibly destructive.

00:01:48.690 --> 00:01:53.260
In Hiroshima, something
like 40% of the population

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:57.480
was killed, more or less
instantly, burns or blasts.

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:00.890
And probably another
20%, 30% died

00:02:00.890 --> 00:02:03.480
within a year of radiation.

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:07.250
So in addition,
people have realized

00:02:07.250 --> 00:02:13.260
that there are severe climate
effects of a nuclear exchange.

00:02:13.260 --> 00:02:16.330
One of the things that happens
with all the burning that

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:22.800
goes on is that soot is
emitted into the atmosphere.

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:25.950
This is the opposite
of global warming.

00:02:25.950 --> 00:02:28.290
This is global cooling.

00:02:28.290 --> 00:02:31.410
This is like a
volcanic explosion.

00:02:31.410 --> 00:02:38.030
And in about 1815, 1816,
there was a volcanic explosion

00:02:38.030 --> 00:02:39.460
in Asia.

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:43.380
And there was a
winter without-- there

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:47.320
was a summer-- excuse me--
there was a summer without crops

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:49.560
in Europe.

00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:52.380
And there was actually
starvation in Europe

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:54.155
due to this explosion.

00:02:54.155 --> 00:02:57.170
It was a one time thing.

00:02:57.170 --> 00:03:03.060
The climate models, for
even a limited nuclear war

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:07.370
in Southeast Asia, show that
this effect would probably

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:12.870
last 5 to 10 years
and be global,

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:15.810
from roughly 100
nuclear weapons.

00:03:15.810 --> 00:03:16.760
So there are papers.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:20.260
I can give people
references if they want.

00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:21.970
There is a paper
in Physics Today

00:03:21.970 --> 00:03:24.470
a few years ago about this.

00:03:24.470 --> 00:03:28.370
But there are many
papers on the subject.

00:03:28.370 --> 00:03:33.400
So one of the things I want
to say-- so the second lecture

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:39.850
will be on proliferation
and uranium enrichment

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:41.140
and the implications.

00:03:41.140 --> 00:03:46.310
So these lectures will combine
both technology and policy.

00:03:46.310 --> 00:03:49.420
And finally, the last
lecture I will give--

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:53.320
and it's kind of an overview of
where we stand on nuclear arms

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:55.120
control and
proliferation-- I'll try

00:03:55.120 --> 00:03:57.230
to fill in some of the gaps.

00:03:57.230 --> 00:04:00.440
I'll talk about the
nonproliferation review that's

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:03.260
coming up at the UN next spring.

00:04:03.260 --> 00:04:08.033
I'll talk about the outlook
for arms control as I see it.

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:14.990
I want to talk a few
minutes to the students

00:04:14.990 --> 00:04:18.769
because one of the things
that's happened over

00:04:18.769 --> 00:04:22.660
the last few decades, since
the collapse of the Soviet

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:28.560
Union in about 1990,
people stopped worrying

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:31.090
about the bomb, so to speak.

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:35.810
Before that, there
was a lot of concern.

00:04:35.810 --> 00:04:39.080
Students were asked to duck
under their desks and things

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:42.780
like that to protect themselves,
which, of course, was totally

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:44.666
ridiculous.

00:04:44.666 --> 00:04:50.700
A wooden desk wouldn't do you
much good in a nuclear war

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:51.700
as you can well imagine.

00:04:54.370 --> 00:04:58.880
It'll just probably knock you
on the head with something.

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:00.504
God knows what it would do.

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:07.510
But the issue has
fallen off the table.

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:09.840
And the thing that
concerns people

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:13.450
more on campus when-- if they
think about global issues,

00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:17.740
is climate change
and global warming.

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:21.750
But this is an issue
which has not gone away.

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:25.950
If anything, the probability
of a nuclear exchange

00:05:25.950 --> 00:05:31.420
is higher now than a
decade ago unfortunately.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:34.300
And we have not
solved these problems.

00:05:34.300 --> 00:05:39.170
And there are political
and economic problems.

00:05:39.170 --> 00:05:41.130
And I just want
to say a few words

00:05:41.130 --> 00:05:45.950
about some of the
intellectual problems that

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:47.910
need to be solved.

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:50.550
For example, on a
technical basis,

00:05:50.550 --> 00:05:54.220
there are inspection issues.

00:05:54.220 --> 00:05:59.850
For example, how do you
inspect whether or not

00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:05.080
a country is cheating on its
nonproliferation obligations?

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:08.080
How do you look for
weapons production

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.680
or enrichment production?

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:14.940
These are very difficult issue,
and they're very difficult

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:17.380
technical issues.

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:20.350
And then there are
issues in which

00:06:20.350 --> 00:06:23.460
you have to combine
technical issues with policy.

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:25.850
For example, if we're
going to go down

00:06:25.850 --> 00:06:28.720
to a very small
number of weapons--

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:31.110
as you want to do
for nuclear arms

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:35.934
control-- then cheating
with a small number--

00:06:35.934 --> 00:06:37.350
particularly if
you're going to go

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:43.310
to 0-- cheating with a small
number becomes a bigger issue.

00:06:43.310 --> 00:06:47.620
So verification issues are
very important, reinventing

00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:50.730
the bomb, if you
really want to zero.

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:55.020
So there are all kinds
of intellectual issues

00:06:55.020 --> 00:07:00.410
that need to be worked out,
both historical, technical,

00:07:00.410 --> 00:07:01.950
and political.

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:07.370
And there are many opportunities
for research in these areas,

00:07:07.370 --> 00:07:09.190
UROP, some theses.

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:11.060
So I just want to
point that out.

00:07:11.060 --> 00:07:15.470
And there are also positions
in government and NGOs.

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:19.860
In the last semester, we
had several major arms

00:07:19.860 --> 00:07:23.870
control negotiators
in the US government,

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:26.300
including Rose
Gottemoeller who was

00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:32.880
the chief negotiator on the US
side for the New START Treaty,

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:37.110
said she was particularly
excited to give a talk at MIT

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:41.810
because we really needed a
generation of technically

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:45.410
trained people to go into
nuclear arms control.

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:50.960
And she made a special plea,
